  "market_context": "NQ daily chart showing an up-close candle that closed below and was retested multiple times before continuing lower. A subsequent daily candle formed with a large upper wick, providing a premium reference for short bias.",
  "key_observation": "The consequent encroachment of the daily candle's large wick acts as a premium reference; price reaches into it without body closure above, then displaces lower, setting up a short toward hourly lows as draw on liquidity.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: On the NQ daily chart, identify the large-wick candle and mark its consequent encroachment (50% of the wick) as the premium reference.",
    "Step 2: Drop to the hourly chart and mark the resting lows below as the draw on liquidity.",
    "Step 3: Observe price reaching into the consequent encroachment of the daily wick with no bodies closing above it, followed by displacement lower.",
    "Step 4: During the New York session, watch for a sweep of an hourly swing high in the opposite direction of the drawn liquidity.",
    "Step 5: Drop to the 5-minute chart after the hourly high sweep; identify the aggressive move out and back into range, then locate a fair value gap.",
    "Step 6: Enter short at the 5-minute fair value gap with stop above the swept high; since targeting the local low only gives 1.14R, use a standard deviation projection instead.",
    "Step 7: Set target at the 2nd standard deviation projection of the manipulation leg, noting that the 4th standard deviation aligns with the hourly drawn liquidity below."
  ],
  "outcome": "Price reached the 2nd standard deviation projection, completing the target.",
  "lessons": "When a sub-2R target exists at the obvious low, use standard deviation projections instead. Daily wick consequent encroachment + hourly draw on liquidity + 5-minute FVG after a session sweep provides a clean top-down short entry.",
